class Solution {
public:
    bool checkInclusion(string s1, string s2) {
       int i=0;
       vector<int>freq1(26,0),freq2(26,0);
       for(int i=0;i<s1.length();i++){
           freq1[s1[i]-'a']++;
       }
       int k=s1.length();
       for(int j=0;j<s2.length();j++){
        freq2[s2[j]-'a']++;
        if(j-i+1>k){
            freq2[s2[i]-'a']--;
            i++;
        }
        if(j-i+1==k){
            if(freq1==freq2){
                return true;
            }
        }
       }
       return false;


    }
};
Step 1: Explain the Idea (Big Picture)

"The main observation is that every permutation of s1 has the same length and the same character frequencies as s1. So instead of generating all permutations, I check every substring of s2 having the same length as s1."

Step 2: Explain the Frequency Arrays
vector<int> freq1(26,0), freq2(26,0);

Say:

"I use two frequency arrays. freq1 stores the frequency of characters in s1, and freq2 stores the frequency of the current window in s2."

Step 3: Build Frequency of s1
for(int i=0; i<s1.length(); i++){
    freq1[s1[i]-'a']++;
}

Say:

"First, I count the frequency of every character in s1."

Step 4: Sliding Window
for(int j=0; j<s2.length(); j++)

Say:

"Now I slide a fixed-size window over s2. The right pointer adds a new character to the window."

freq2[s2[j]-'a']++;

"I add the current character to the window frequency."

If the window becomes larger than s1.length():

if(j-i+1 > k){
    freq2[s2[i]-'a']--;
    i++;
}

Say:

"If the window size becomes greater than s1.length(), I remove the leftmost character and move the left pointer so that the window size remains fixed."

Step 5: Compare Frequencies
if(j-i+1 == k){
    if(freq1 == freq2){
        return true;
    }
}

Say:

"Whenever the window size becomes equal to s1.length(), I compare the frequency of the current window with the frequency of s1. If both are equal, it means the current window is a permutation of s1, so I return true."
